# Runtime Alternatives — {{team_name}}

> The reference impl ships a bash + cron + Telegram substrate (see
> `reference-impl/` and `BUILD.md`). This file documents alternatives
> the build session may pick instead, with tradeoffs.

## Decision frame

The runtime layer has six responsibilities:

1. **Wake** — fire each agent on its trigger
2. **State** — persist memory, inbox, last-run across wakes
3. **Reason** — invoke the agent's reasoning loop
4. **Gate** — enforce kill-switch + blast-radius approvals
5. **Log** — append-only audit trail
6. **Notify** — send approval requests + escalations + briefings

The contracts in `governance/` define what each must do. The runtime
chooses HOW.

## Option matrix

| Runtime | Best fit | Strengths | Weaknesses |
|---|---|---|---|
| **bash + cron + Telegram (reference-impl)** | Self-hosted VPS / SMB pilots | Zero new deps; debuggable; works offline | Single-machine; no horizontal scaling; bash-shaped error handling |
| **n8n self-hosted (Docker)** | Visual flows + non-technical operators | First-class branching; 600+ node integrations; visual debug | Adds Docker dep; flows are JSON in DB, harder to version-control |
| **n8n cloud** | Demos + non-technical pilots | No infra; same flows as self-hosted | Recurring cost; data residency questions |
| **Pipedream** | Event-driven heavy + serverless | Free tier generous; webhook-native; per-step debugging | Vendor lock-in; cold starts; pricing past free tier |
| **Temporal** | Durable, long-running, retry-heavy workflows | Workflow durability + retries are first-class; battle-tested | Steep learning curve; needs Temporal cluster; overkill for SMB |
| **Inngest** | Durable workflows, simpler than Temporal | Hosted + self-hosted; declarative; great DX | Newer; smaller ecosystem |
| **Custom Python (APScheduler + FastAPI)** | Python-native team; data science integration | Full control; ecosystem rich for data work | Build it yourself; you own ops |
| **Claude Code Scheduled Tasks** | Demo / personal / Mac-Desktop only | Native Claude Code | Tasks expire after 7 days; needs Desktop app open |

## When each wins

### Reference-impl (bash + cron) wins when:

- The team runs on a VPS or self-hosted Linux box
- Cost is a primary constraint (zero new deps)
- The team is comfortable in bash (or willing to learn the small subset)
- Debuggability matters more than ergonomics
- The team is < 10 agents and < 1000 wake/day total

### n8n (self-hosted or cloud) wins when:

- The user / operator will hand-edit flows visually
- Most agents already have tier 3 NEEDS-N8N-FLOW integrations
- Branching logic dominates the workflow shape
- The team wants a UI for monitoring without building one
- Audit + RBAC need a UI that the operator uses (n8n has both)

Tradeoff: n8n hosts the flows in its own DB. Spec-folder generation +
the inventory's `.json` flow stubs work, but version-controlling a
mature n8n DB is a separate problem.

### Pipedream wins when:

- The team is primarily event-driven (webhooks dominate)
- The team needs serverless (no VPS)
- The free tier is sufficient for the scale
- Vendor lock-in is acceptable

### Temporal / Inngest wins when:

- Workflows run for hours/days with retries
- Agent failures must be exactly-once recoverable
- The deployer has Temporal/Inngest experience
- The team has scale that justifies the operational complexity

### Custom Python wins when:

- The team has Python DNA
- Integration with pandas, numpy, scikit, etc. is part of the work
- Custom RBAC / audit / metrics infrastructure is required
- The team can fund + maintain its own runtime

## Migration paths

If the team starts on reference-impl and outgrows it:

| Outgrowing | Migrate to | Migration effort |
|---|---|---|
| Single machine, can't scale horizontally | Custom Python (Celery / Dramatiq) | Days |
| Visual flow ergonomics | n8n self-hosted | Days |
| Need durable retries | Inngest (hosted) or Temporal | Weeks |
| Compliance / RBAC requirements | Custom Python + IAM integration | Weeks |

The CONTRACTS in `governance/` stay constant — only the implementations
change. That's the point of separating spec from runtime.

## Migration paths IN

If the team starts on a hosted runtime and wants to bring it in-house:

| From | To | Migration effort |
|---|---|---|
| n8n cloud → n8n self-hosted | Same flows, different infra | Hours |
| Pipedream → custom Python | Reimplement event handlers | Days |
| Claude Code Scheduled Tasks → reference-impl | Same prompts, swap scheduler | Hours |

## Cost comparison (rough order of magnitude)

| Runtime | Monthly cost (this team's scale) |
|---|---|
| reference-impl on $5/mo VPS | $5 + Anthropic API |
| n8n self-hosted on $5/mo VPS | $5 + Anthropic API |
| n8n cloud (starter) | $20 + Anthropic API |
| Pipedream (basic) | $0-19 + Anthropic API |
| Temporal Cloud (starter) | $200 + Anthropic API |
| Inngest (free tier) | $0 + Anthropic API (until cap) |

The Anthropic API cost is the same regardless of runtime — it's the
agents' reasoning, not the orchestration.

## What NOT to use

| Avoid | Why |
|---|---|
| **Bare AWS Lambda + EventBridge** without a framework | You'll rebuild the contracts; pick Inngest or Pipedream instead |
| **Airflow** | Built for batch ETL, not multi-agent reactive workflows |
| **Generic CI runners** (Jenkins, GitHub Actions) | Not designed for long-lived state + Telegram I/O |
| **Cron alone** without the helpers | You'll reinvent `gen_correlation_id`, `audit_log`, etc. |

## Recommendation per team profile

| Profile | Recommended runtime |
|---|---|
| Solo founder / SMB / Spain pilot | reference-impl on $5/mo VPS |
| Non-technical operator team | n8n self-hosted |
| Event-driven heavy | Pipedream or n8n |
| Enterprise + compliance | Custom Python OR Temporal Cloud |
| Hackathon / demo | Claude Code Scheduled Tasks |

When in doubt, default to reference-impl. It's the lowest-risk path
to a working team. Migrate later if you outgrow it.

